                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.00 Revolutions/5: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-07-25T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 25, 1931—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>77. I talked this afternoon with Frodden, Chief of the Cabinet. He said
                    emphatically that the armed forces are supporting the President, <pb facs="1019"
                        n="905" xml:id="pg_905"/> that the government has the situation in hand not
                    only in Santiago but in north and south, and that the President has no intention
                    to resign. He spoke with confidence and resolve. I submit this statement merely
                    as the view of the government. As we spoke we could look through the windows of
                    the Moneda upon machine guns which command the streets and upon heavily armed
                    troops.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
